content: So nice to see you all here! So many of you
Especially warm welcome to those 20 new members who joined recently
I hope you will all enjoy the studies here and make many new friends
Since we have many new members today, we will take the lesson a bit slower tempo
First, we will do the participation check.
Please see the I am Here button below board
and press it when the check begins

claire, killer21st, shuwang, Morden, dittp, Red_Zombie, coco_yuang, span, paradise, jamphen, Before, mumax, shai1144, Intotherenju, iris, LiuJianping, johanna, smiling, Fredde, luwenzhe, weigui, virag, ermine, yyfcsd, sosei, alcore, Chaos, shuker.
Now we will go on with lesson.
Today we will analyse a game from the WC 2003 again.
wow!why i cant take the 1st place?:(
It is so useful to analyse good players' games,
and try to understand what happened there.
you guys see the I am here button ?
The black player was Martin Carlsson,
the white player was Konstantin Chingin
They are both quite young players,
chingin is very cool ... I mean calm
Chingin is the Youth European Champion 2003
He got the 4th place in WC 2003
Carlsson does not have titles yet,
but he has made good progress in recent years,
and has become a dangerous opponent to everyone.
If I remember right, it has not been played in WC since 1995.
The top players consider i6 opening as black sure win.
And nobody wants to take the risk of playing it.
chingin tried this opening several times in this WC and got quite good result
All the people in WC watched that game with big interest and question - what trap will there be
This 4th move has raised some questions before,
but yet, there is some varient of 5th moves,
Chingin took the chance and brought it up to the WC.
What do we know about the 5th moves here?
if you dont know, you can try to guess
I guess, J8 is a veyr important point of white
so in some way, black got to block that
g8 is the same with I9 opening.
thanks, good job all of you
it gives sure black win as we know it
This 5th move is considered as the main alternative move
but apparently Chingin had some traps here as well.
and he chose this 5th move instead.
lets see how it comes from i4
I remember, long time ago, in 1995,
I made lots of analyses here about black attack,
and I remember having found the wins everywhere for black.
But it has been a long time,
and lots of things were forgotten.
Chingin disclosed his gambling tactics with move 12 -
from this point we knew what he was doing here.
There are different possibilities for black,
move 12 doesn't made by the opponent?
but Carlsson attacked from move 13 until the end of the game by VCT.
Chingin was white here, Carlsson black
But after the game, I heard different comments.
Carlsson: I had a sure win from 19th move... need to check other 18th.
Chingin: There was no sure win for black, white had at least two defenses later on.
Is next 34 considered as a move in VCT?
I analysed the game with Chingin later,
and I realized he was right - he could have saved the game,
if he had not made a mistake in game.
We will now see how it all happened.
But before that, lets make one HERE check.

killer21st, leto, yyfcsd, alcore, Intotherenju, dittp, claire, LiuJianping, Chaos, shuwang, weigui, smiling, iris, Before, span, luwenzhe, jamphen, johanna, Morden, Fredde, ermine, whte, shai1144, Red_Zombie, dadisheng, paradise, yellow, zjjwf, shaoping.
Carlsson was attacking in most direct style.
Here I remember Chingin spent lots of time,
you can tell, just guess, or maybe you can figure out why
to make a four or not
I guess he has almost fully computed black moves during that 1 hr
hard to think from his stand :(
shai1144, of course, m10 is the block. but why did he think 1 hour before moving there?
so you all can find it
I think that white maybe think if it win by VCT?
but why would he need to think about playing a four?
guess if black make L6, that point can connect downwords and right at the same time
it will be a very strong move
take L6 would somewhat block black's connection ? safer ?
and explain through our theory of tactics:
he was thinking of using the four, based on the worry of white taking the L6 point next
we only use the four when we have to
and the situations are: own VCF, forced defense, or worry that opponent thats that point
so all is just like we learned before
he was sure black would go L6 next,
But he spent 1 hour to compare,
what is better for white - to let black go L6, or to play self L6 and let black be at m5 + tempo
Do you all understand now why he spent 1 hour here?
tempo, means, timing to make your own move
after long thinking, he realized, he cannot use the four,
because the outcome would be worse for him
I may be wrong - maybe he spent more than 1 hour there.
I forgot, because I had my own game to play same time
so I cannot record every detail
There are two variants that have some interest.
then we would have to ask ourselves,
perhaps black could just use four first to k6, and then L6,
to save all the trouble of finding win from 18-k6
here we have two blocks to check now
but maybe we can play four to k6 first, to simplify the attack.
Anyway, it is the matter of analysis.
Here, it was black's turn again, and Carlsson was thinking hard here.
Chingin stood up, and walked around...
at some point, he was not far from my table,
and I heard them speaking in Russian language,
Sushkov told Chingin about the "cut" there, defending the attack
they can speak to others during the game?
It is not allowed to speak in their language,
and definitely not about games, during the round
Maybe Sushkov was trying to comfort Chingin,
they missed Ando's lesson about ethics
without seeing the end of that game.
Later we came back to tournament hall,
and that game was over too, the records showed - Carlsson won.
I wanted to know what happened there then, and what was the "cut" there doing and where was it.
Carlsson showed me the game first.
He was very happy over his win.
From which side it is necessary to block?
what's the reason for 22, Mr Ando?
indeed, we need to block from the bottom
So , this move here is necessary
for 22, it seems we can block from the top
who wants to show win, say me
but if it was me, i will make 27 ahead of 25
it is possible to change the order of moves here
but there are positions in renju where only one unique order can succeed
I think I should say thanks to span too.
Soon became clear, where the cut was.
now, black has two VCF threats
Likely, Chingin was worried about the diagonal line h9_i10
and he wanted to block it
Now, white has only one way to block both VCFs, where?
But now, Carlsson found winning attack
no need to know the game record
give you some time to think first
good, our new student Don will try
Carlsson played these two fours first,
but Don's win was even shorter by one move
After I had spoke to Carlsson,
I asked his comment about the game.
And he said he made a mistake with move 28.
He had a choice between three 28th moves,
and he chose the only losing one,
i guess he hasn't thought much on this move
while other two would have defended
as you see, black cannot really use the connection 5_29,
so, there is no worry of that diagonal line.
same way, but thanks to stone 28 in better location
this is a very big mistake for chingin I think
you shouldn't have lost that easily
but he was under big time trouble by then
because I was out at that time
Now, who would want to be a volunteer,
The purpose now is to show that this 28th move (L7) could defend also.
So I will try to simulate attack here, and killer21st will defend.
that this 28th move was also defense
nice, i didn't see i12 move
so, a big unluck - to choose the only losing 28th move.
But time pressure must have been very big.
Now we know that white could have defended this game,
how much time was he left at that move
and we have a big question in mind,
do you have this question too?
while I go back to the 20th move here, lets have one HERE check. Please press now.

it has a counter three, thats the purpose of his  21

to make sure that after correct 28 there is no win
so he will play another 21 instead
I think if there is enough time, then yes
how long will that be ... my god
It was my game with Mr Iio
how much time do u need to chect that three variation of 28 and make the right move, Mr. Ando?
here, before I made next move,
and u also count the defense?
that took a long time ... over one hour .... but still magic
what makes this counting hard is:
1. there are all branches to check
oh non i haven't time  to...
2. you dont know if there is win or not
if you know there must be win, you are more motivated
that's what this game's purpose, u got to improve ur depth of computation to be stronger,:)
I used the same counting method
as I told you in the article before
i had to foresee them all
The difficult thing for me was:
when i was thinking the ending here...
very effectively used the upper board :))
but i checked over and over again, i didnt see naything
so, it is possible to count like 20 own stones of VCF,
if you have enough thinking time,
you call that medium or advanced problem?
if you can use stones, its not so hard maybe
but to see all from here,
without stones, may make you very tired
the player can actually check from here,
to make sure there is no win with 23-j10
RT, maybe you need a nap.
Carlsson, maybe to eager to win,
then, you can give us more things.
Sometimes, the "advantage" side is influenced by the timetrouble of opponent
that subconciously makes the player make moves faster
to not give the opponent chance to recover
the pressure on time was successful tactics
and he got the win from no-win position.
But lets now check the alternatives.
did Chingin know all about this before the tornment?
I guess he didnt have much analysis here, or else why think 1 hour about move 16
i guess upto 21, those are very natual moves
both 21-m7 and 21-m9 work, maybe m9 easier, not worry about counter 3.

there you just need to show win

Was it white win or not?
ok, let me quickly explain how to record homework,
in each time when it is "attacker's" turn, you have to show ALL possible attack moves.
and for those all moves, show ONE opponent block for EACH of them
and then, afte that, ALL possible attack moves
and ONE block to block each of those attack moves
and the failure of win was proved
we want to prove here white cant win
now we need to write down
and we need to prove attacker cant win
to prove that, the defender makes ONE move in eahc level
and attacker makes ALL possible attack moves
so black (defender) makes just ONE move
which you think is the defense
attacker will show all branches here now
and lets for example enter into one of the branches
do not play more than ONE defense if you are proving the position can be defended
and attacker must play ALL posible attack moves here
but atacker has more possibiities than defender!!!!!
oh my god ... that will take forever ...
the number of variants is about same
in each turn you played ONE attacker move
then ONE attack, then ALL defense
when you prove defense, then ALL attack, and ONE defense
its very hard for me to select white attack points
the more you check the better
but you can skip very irrelevant attacks
if you dont show this attack, i dont mind
because it has no influence on main attack
you need to show all posible attack moves when its attackers turn
and when it is defenders turn, then just one move
but defender doesnt expand the tree
and the last column of the table is the student answers
And I and other senior members are always here and in forum,
to help and advise you, if you have questions.
we are all here as a one happy team
now we will end the lesson
good day to all of you!
